segments.text: I brought him down here, met with the president and everybody else and the Board of Regents.
And they called the Athletic Council in with the Board of Regents and interviewed Jackie.
And I said, Jackie, tell me.
I said, how would you feel being treated the way Tom Wilson was treated in this process?
He said, John, he said, the question is, do you want to win or not?
I mean, that's the issue you're looking at.
And I said, well, would the Board of Regents have the control over this appointing a football coach like they have you?
And, of course, I know Chuck Sampson and others were backing off when I was asking this.
But they all agreed that we wanted to win.
And then I'm interviewed by CBS right out here.
John McDermott and I were asked to be interviewed about the football coach.
John said, I think it's an unmitigated disaster that a football coach make that much and professors are barely making it.
We don't have this and that.
I said, and I didn't use my little bite.
I said, well, I don't have 80,000 people come to one of my seminars, and our board wants to be number one in whatever we try to do.
And I got a nice teaching award the other year a while back, and I'm not making near that much money, but I don't draw 80,000 people to my class either.
Well, they didn't use mine, but they used John, and John had the nice long hair, you know.
Interesting time.
As far as you know, who was the person or persons that identified Cheryl?
Oh, I think probably, if you want to look at it, certainly McKenzie, Lindsay.
in my recollection.
You mean John Lynch?
Yeah.
Really?
Yeah.
Speaker of the House at the time.
Billy Clayton.
Billy Clayton.
They were some of the people that
identified him because he just had a national championship team.
He had the great quarterback that later played for Miami Dolphins.
So you were on the athletic council?
I was on the council.
We were really tied into everything then.
How long after he got here did you serve?
You know, through the time that he was dismissed.
Oh, really?
See, we were called over to Bill Mobley's office, about three of us.
And the head of the Board of Regents called Bill while we were in the office.
And this is how I remember it.
He said, we've got some real questions about where we're going to fire, the coach or not.
We've got some questions on the board here.
Some want to keep him.
And Bill basically said,
if you don't fire him, you've got to get rid of me.
I'll never forget that.
It got kind of tense.
Tom Adair was there, someone else.
We were in Bill's office because the head of the Board of Regents at the time knew we had to do something, but they didn't want to let him go because they had so much pressure from former students.
And Bill took a real strong stand on that, and I respected him for it, even though, hey, Sheryl was a great football coach.
Cheryl turned around our phobia about orange and white.
We now can beat the University of Texas.
Before that, we didn't think we could.
Did the Athletic Council have any knowledge of whether or not there were some violations under Cheryl?
We did.
We did.
I remember our group.
I had a little subcommittee with some of the best faculty on campus, and we said, don't play a young man named Flowers from Bryan.
Arkansas beat us 28 to nothing up in the hills.
Next thing I know, Flowers is playing.
Then we had a little meeting with the associate dean of agriculture, education, and others, where a lot of the players were, worrying about eligibility.
And I'll never forget this.
The great associate dean of agriculture, been there for years.
Potts.
It was his associate, gray-headed guy.
I think he's out of that role now.
Not R.C.
Potts?
No, Potts was the dean.
You know who I'm talking about.
Tremendous with students.
Curtis Lard?
No.
Not Murray Milford?
Not Murray.
He was there for a long, long time.
Well, he and Brian Cole and another associate dean sitting around the table with me chairing that committee, and Cheryl says,
Let me tell you something.
I can interview a young man and tell you whether he's going to make it or not.
I don't have to worry about some of these test scores and other things.
When I'm recruiting a kid, I know who can make it or not.
And I'm not sure you guys can.
And I said, Coach Sherrill, you're looking at two people right here who have saved more kids than Jesus Christ.
They do know kids.
And I said, that's not the way to approach it.
And then we knew Flowers was playing.
Then we knew the Smith thing came out of Georgia.
And then he was gone.
Yeah, he violated.
Because Bill Mobley handled it rather courageously, didn't he?
He did, very courageously.
Very much so, because I'm not kidding you.
The head of the Board of Regents says, we want to keep him.
He says, you keep him, I'm gone.
That's the impression I had.
Well, that's what we heard that day in that office.
And this was on a weekend.
It was on a Friday.
That's what I thought.
It was on a Friday.
And, you know, my memory's pretty good on that one in terms of.
Who else deserves athletic counsel during that era?
Who else deserves pats on the back for standing up for the right?
I think Tom Adair.
Tom is a solid citizen, man.
He wants to win, but Tom has been the conscience, I think, of the Athletic Council for 15 years.
That's what I thought.
Yeah.
To the typist, you don't need to put this in the final version, but I suggested Tom to Jarvis Miller to be added to the committee.
there was a vacancy and they needed somebody from science.
And they said, who do you think?
And I said, I think that Tom, he's a good solid faculty member, good scholar.
He's interested in athletics, but he's not going to sell out.
That's right.
That's right.
And that's.
So he had me, he and Frank Vandiver had me write a concept paper.
We started getting a lot of pressure from soccer and lacrosse and rugby.
And they had me write a concept paper on what club sports are versus what they got to do to earn their way in.
And Tom then took that, you know, trusting me completely, took that to Vandiver, and that's how women's soccer became a Division I sport because they followed the rules.
Rugby kept drinking the beer and raising a little hell here, you know, fighting here, but wearing A&M uniforms.
Boy, the soccer women, they got it in line and played good competition and became a varsity sport.
And...
Vandiver did so much for this university that I think the people never really gave him credit for.
For a second, or a little longer than a second, describe your impression of Chuck Sampson as Athletic Council Chairman.
Chuck was so thorough, such a gentleman, had been a varsity tennis player at Notre Dame, so he knew competition.
We all knew and respected him.
I just see where he got the highest honor in Texas for an engineering profession.
He knew his stuff.
He loved athletics, but yet integrity was what... That's written all over Chuck Sampson, and you could just see it, and it prevailed, I think, with that athletic council.
People accuse me of being a former athlete, of getting in bed with the athletics, but no, not at all, because I knew we had to have the kind of integrity that...
We needed, because after having Bear Bryant years behind us and some other black marks that we shouldn't have had, I should say ugly marks, we were trying to make it right.
Did any coach or politician or board member ever try to influence your vote on the council?
They did when Jackie Sherrill came in here.
I wasn't ready to hire him from my perspective.
It was done without our wishes.
The Board of Regents brought him in here over our wishes.
Did anybody call you or write you about
Bill McKenzie talked with me.
He said, isn't he a good one, John?
You know, we need to move into the next level.
So, yeah, there was some pressure.
I don't know whether pressure for the other people, but Bill Romaine, I guess, went to his grave angry over firing Tom Wilson.
Tom had had an 8-2 year, but people said, oh, he's not tough enough.
He couldn't be.
We need to go after big time.
And Tom never really forgave us, even though he sent players here.
went on to win a state high school title.
Did any coach ever try to twist your arm?
Not really, not really.
I didn't teach undergraduates.
I remember at times I was asked by a basketball coach for some courses to get some kids in so they could stay eligible.
But there wasn't any of that on the football side, RC especially.
And I just really didn't get to know Emory that well since I'd just come on at the end of his time.
But, no, there's never been an instant.
Your perception of Marvin Tate as the athletic director during that period?
I think Marvin Tate was so good.
Articulate spokesperson, had been in business world,
I don't know why.
I guess over the coaching change and Tom Wilson thing, there was something I never really understood.
But Marvin didn't last long after the Jackie Sherrill.
We wound up with Jackie wanting to be both AD and head coach.
Then, of course, John David Crowe came in and did that.
I think Marvin probably got a bad deal.
I thought he was very articulate.
I thought he knew sports.
He loved A&M.
I never understood that one very well.
Now, did he survive the Sherrill dismissal?
Yeah, he survived that, but then he was gone as soon as, you know, he was gone soon after that.
Okay.
Yeah.
Because he wound up being sort of the associate
Athletic director to Cheryl, see.
Does R.C.
follow Cheryl?
Yeah.
Were you on the council when he was selected as head coach?
I'm trying to think.
I don't think so.
I'd just gone off.
Okay.
Because that would have been about 1986 or 678.
I went off in 88.
Okay.
It would have been about that time.
Yeah, about that time.
I remember how elated I was when they appointed R.C.
because I knew
What a good person he was, yeah.
Typist, this is not for inclusion.
I'm just sharing an anecdote with him.
One of the interesting things coming up, Bob Stull, who is the AD at UTEP, did I tell you the relation between him and R.C.?
No, I know the name Stull, though.
All right.
They were half-time, beginning, first-year assistant, assistant coaches at Kansas State.
Is that right?
Years ago.
I remember that.
And one night, after some cool beverages, they did a handshake agreement that if either one of them ever became a head coach, he'd hire the other one.
Then after that job, their first full-time assistant job was at Kent State, and Dick Tamburo...
was the assistant athletic director.
And the man who would later be the very, very, very fine head coach for the Washington Huskies, whose name escapes me right now.
I don't know who you're talking about.
He was their head coach.
Yeah.
And a guy who had later owned the El Paso Diablos very successful baseball franchise was a first-year intern sports information director.
And so...
Then when I hire Stull as a head coach for the fall of 86.
Yeah, yeah, I remember that.
He called RC and said, okay.
I'll hire you.
And he said R.C.
told him, no, there's some things developing here that I might have a chance to be a head coach here.
I'll be darned.
And so then when I get to Missouri, Tamburo, I make him the A.D., then he and I hire Stull.
And so now Stull is back as A.D. there, and he's going to play R.C.
And another tiny link, both R.C.
and I went to Orange High School.
I knew you both went to Orange High School, yeah.
That's right.
That's good.
Let's see.
Other extracurricular tasks you had during all those years?
The primary, of course, was the athletic council and the faculty senate.
I was also elected to the first executive committee of the faculty senate.
There were five of us.
What did it do?
It was a titular head, really.
I mean, we were the ones that worked closely with the speaker.
We then oversaw the committees within the Senate.
And it was a pretty time-consuming thing.
We got a lot of things done.
A core curriculum came out of that.

A lot of our faculty concerns, we began with inclusion and minority issues for faculty, recruiting faculty, changing the structure of the department head from more of a chair approach to more a decentralized approach.
Paul Parrish was on that.
I'm trying to think of all the other people on that.
Bill Barzak was on the first.
We had to be elected by the faculty senate.
And the woman in biochemistry was on that.
I can't think of her name.
And how often did the senate and the executive committee meet?
We met once a month, once a month.
The executive committee, of course,
met before the Faculty Senate met.
About how many on the Senate?
There were about 80, yeah, roughly about 80.
The time you got some of the larger colleges had four or five representatives.
We had two or three.
And then we had, of course, the staff.
Might have been about 60, I guess, probably about 60.
And were there some big, as you look back,
Were there some big issues that y'all were not able to get anything, any action on?
Our biggest issue was we had to back off on some of the humanities courses because of the so-called accreditation problems of the College of Engineering.
And there was some consternation over that.
Humanities?
Yeah.
There was consternation of not having well-educated engineers and the same battle that goes on all the time.
Those were some of the biggest ones, I think, right there.
The women issue of feminism, those kinds of things are just beginning to become present.
And the lack of discussion about lack of faculty, women faculty, minority faculty.
And I think it was a healthy kind of beginning for, the fermentation was there, I think, to begin making changes in the faces of our faculty.
All right.
Vandiver, you gave him credit for being sensitive as the president.
What other administrators do you think were faculty senate sensitive?
I think at that time we had our dean of faculties who'd come out of the College of Business.
Clint Phillips.
Clint.
was very supportive, I thought.
And having Bill Barzak involved, who had been through some of those chairs, just having him as part of the faculty senate was very helpful as well.
Looking back on it, those were some of the major players, I think.
There were a lot of people opposed to the Faculty Senate.
And what did your colleagues think about your role?
Well, they thought that I should be able to, one, speak well for the College of Education in terms of what our disciplines are, what we're trying to do, and how critical we are to the whole process.
And they figured that I was strong enough to be able to
stand up chin to chin with anybody in any discipline.
They expected me to do that.
And I did my best to do that as well.
Did a department head or a dean ever give you any counsel about your faculty senate role?
Not really.
Because we had this subcommittee within, I would call the caucus.
And we'd ask the dean if there's anything we needed to fight for.
One thing I did fight hard for, and I still think it was a mistake, we needed a course in the social sciences and education on what education is all about in America.

So every undergraduate here who winds up on school boards or supporting schools to understand what they are, education as a discipline, what it is, and I fought for that and tried to get it entered, and I couldn't get enough support even within the college because they didn't know who was going to teach it.
So I'm not for it unless my department.
That's right.
That's right.
And I thought it had been a great idea.
I remember fighting that with two or three of them.
Our caucus really thought that made sense.

You know, if you understand what political science is about, once you understand that education is the key to our country, why not have a good, interesting, fascinating course, not a boring course, on the politics and the history of American education.
So that was an issue we fought on that I didn't win on.
Now, you said you're going to a 4 o'clock.
Yeah, 4 o'clock.
What time do you want to take off?
Ten more minutes, I'm fine.
Okay.
When Frank Hubert became chancellor, what happened in the college in terms of leadership?
Well, we started the search, and a few of us were interested in becoming dean after that because I was being invited to apply elsewhere.
And we had other candidates who were qualified or better than I, but...
We found Dean Corrigan.
He was dean at the University of Maryland.
He came in here and interviewed, and everybody was very impressed with him.
He was not an authoritarian.
He was a totally different personality from Frank Hubert.
As far as you recall, was he the general favorite of the group?
Yes, very much so.
He proved to be a really good dean.
He was more effective externally than he was internally, in my opinion.
He was working with Ross Perot on a key committee to determine where we went.
We lost some ground there in terms of only 18 hours of education and lost a so-called education major.
But he fought hard on Perot on that one.
He did some good stuff with us in terms of inquiry groups, doing a lot of interdisciplinary kinds of things.
But he was a kind, thoughtful, bright person.
who never embarrassed us in any way, and as far as I know, never intimidated anybody like past deans who will go unmentioned.
After he left, we had a bad situation here.
We brought in a person, a woman from University of Houston, Stallings.
In many ways, she was very divisive, and the college almost, it was like, really it was a vote of no confidence for her.
Was there a real search?
Not a really good search, I think.
We did a real search, but somehow, and the people at the University of Houston, she was department head down there, said she wasn't an administrator.
But she had a lot of federal grants, had a big name, and the provost wanted somebody who could bring in money to the college like other colleges do.
Which provost?
McDonnell.
McDonnell?
Yeah.
And she had a lot of grants.
Was there...
Was there a perception that there was a deliberate effort to hire a female?
I think so.
And this was a good college to start in since we tend to have a lot of women in the program.
I don't think there's any question about that.
And she had the name.
Hold her on the scholarship.
But from the get-go, she was not an administrator and didn't understand how to be an administrator.
and almost tore the college apart.
She lasted how long?
Three years.
Two, really.
Now, Dean Corrigan ceased being dean.
Why?
He was just ready to do something else.
He got the Harrington chair, you know, is in our department, and I think he just, he was tired.
Because there certainly was no dissatisfaction.
There was no dissatisfaction, not at all, except for us losing that power base across the state.
We'll never understand why we didn't have enough influence and why he didn't have enough influence with his name and with his prestige.
And I think in many ways he may have felt like that he may have disappointed some of us.
But I don't think in terms of our wishing he would step out, there was none of that.
But man, there was with Stallings from the get-go.
Then following her.
Station-wide search.
I went back on Stallings.
We had a guy hired named Miller from Missouri.
I think his name's Miller.
He was either dean at the University of Missouri at the time or had been at the University of Missouri.
I think that's right.
Yeah.
We had him hired.
But the provost said no.
We don't want him.
He had sort of an industrial arts vocational background.
And then she gets the job.
And that made a lot of people mad because they'd gone through the search.
Jane came to us, having not been a dean, been an associate dean, Jane Connolly.
But wait, following Stallings, is Jane Connolly next?
Yeah.
Jane, Jane.
It was a problem with some of us getting the right name.
She came in without experience, having been an administrator, but a good scholar.
And this is about when?
That's been four years ago.
Okay.
Some of us had concern because of being an Ed Psych type who may not have the background link to make the links.
The problem is a lot of the Ed Administration types don't want to be deans.
They just don't want to do that, and so the Ed Psych people come in who aren't administrative trained, who are not public school people usually, and so we were a little leery about that.
But she's come in and she's done a wonderful job.
She's dealt with some tough issues.
But I think she's been very successful, much better administrator, much better.
She, Stallings was trying in many ways to change the gender balance too quickly.
And Jane's come in with people of color and gender and balanced them really well.
So that's the difference.
One used a hammer, one used a shoehorn.
Let's stop there.
Okay.
August 31st.
John, some missed opportunities.
Can you think of any missed opportunities that
this college might have taken advantage of?
Yes.

I think the effort coming out of the land-grant tradition of really becoming a service institution as well as a research-based institution, I think in the spirit of this university really, this college,
trying to be so careful about modeling the liberal arts and science colleges in terms of its type of scholarship.
I truly believe that we've had several opportunities to truly become a service university for the state of Texas and the nation.
We have outstanding researchers.
We've done some wonderful things in collaboration with schools.
We started here under Dean Corrigan, an inquiry group, and started working with school systems to set up a research collaborative.
Well, that went by the wayside when Corrigan left.
And the whole idea on being a reservoir of creating knowledge.

opposed to really emphasizing the service elements and helping the schools especially urban schools let's call them to the wayside that we're doing a lot of new things but we're just now trying to recover from that because we so i think in the long run as a professional school we may have lost something lost some opportunities
that uh not to make you recover but there's some there's still some damage i think um i think
And one of the efforts we tried to, I think, reach out in the late 80s,

our department dr erlinson and i worked together to create a one of the first cohort doctoral programs in the country that was really workable where we looked at the edd program people who could not come in full-time for residency and actually build a cohort where we select them together from the school district and each of those people not only working doctors they were contributing into the school district and we built some tremendous liaisons in fact we hired the superintendent
from San Antonio gave these fees to be on our clinical faculty.
so-called
And I'm meeting this next week with the gentlemen from Richardson Foundation.

They've asked me to take on this challenge of developing a document for the future of superintendents in Texas in a time of great change where superintendents are aging and where schools and universities have to build a bridge.
And I've written a piece, I think I told you last week,
We want to be highly productive.
We want to produce in the journals that are seen scholarly.
Not the way I would like it to happen.
Yeah, we've got partnerships.
We've got public school, university liaisons going of all kinds.
But in terms of a financial commitment, in terms of a state political commitment, no.
We're still K-12 and higher ed, and don't let those funds get mixed up.
I think probably University of North Texas.
is really, come on, that's gonna do these big things in the Metroplex.
I think UT Arlington.
UT Arlington has a wonderful national program.

They've got the British Foundation of Money, and they actually have a superintendent in their entire area, so that's a big star, and give them a full-time paid internship, and you do your degree through the UTA program there.
That is a wonderful program.
I think, probably,
Thank you.
